49":"1325–1349","1325–1391":"1325–1391","1349":"1349","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","24 June 1391":"24 June 1391","1391":"1391","1449":"1449","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","Melcombe, Dorset, , England":"Dorset, England","England":"England","Melcombe Bingham, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorset, England":"Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorset, , England":"Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Turgis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Turgoose  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Turgoose","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Turgis</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>Þorgils</i>,  <i>Thorgisl</i>).  Compare  Sturgess  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Turgis was born in 1345, in Dorset, England, his father, John Turgis, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth Joseph, was 20. He married Mrs Richard Turgis in 1369, in Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1449, in his hometown, at the age of 104."},"et":{"1345–1449":"1345–1449","1349–1449":"1349–1449","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1325–1349":"1325–1349","1325–1391":"1325–1391","1349":"1349","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","24 June 1391":"24. juuni 1391","1391":"1391","1449":"1449","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","Melcombe, Dorset, , England":"Dorset, England","England":"England","Melcombe Bingham, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorset, England":"Mappowder, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorse